{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486885"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:48:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:48:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"200"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/200"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.03,0.18,0.07,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"200"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53480"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/200"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"200"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38949"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"111"},{"type":"tags","id":"244"},{"type":"tags","id":"1287"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9098"},{"type":"tags","id":"9099"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4382"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15797"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42026"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43787"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53480"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of severe abdominal pain. The pain is colicky in nature and generalised. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, atrial fibrillation and coronary artery stent insertion following a myocardial infarction four years ago. His medications include metformin, metoprolol, ramipril, aspirin and clopidogrel. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 90/min and irregular, blood pressure 130/90mmHg and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. The abdominal examination shows that his abdomen is soft with mild, diffuse tenderness, but no guarding. On initial investigations haematological and biochemical values are within normal limits. Supportive measures, including IV access, IV fluids and antibiotics are initiated.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT angiography","Apixaban","Formal abdominal ultrasound","Exploratory laparotomy","Superior mesenteric artery angioplasty"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe working diagnosis is acute mesenteric ischaemia. A hallmark feature is pain out of proportion to clinical findings - often these patients will have abdominal pain without peritonism. Based on the patient\u2019s history and probable atrial fibrillation (irregular pulse), acute mesenteric arterial embolism is likely the underlying cause of the ischaemia. The site and extent of the vascular occlusion, as well as the extent of bowel ischaemia must be determined, and \u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiography\u003C/strong\u003E is the most expeditious way of achieving this, having a sensitivity of \u0026gt;90% and specificity of nearly 100%. For the sicker patient, with evidence of sepsis and/or peritonitis, it would be more appropriate to consider direct surgical intervention via an \u003Cstrong\u003Eexploratory laparotomy \u003C/strong\u003Efor resection of non-viable bowel and revascularisation via embolectomy. Given this patient is haemodynamically stable without peritonism or sepsis, laparotomy is not urgently indicated and further information should be gathered via CT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnticoagulation, such as with \u003Cstrong\u003Eapixaban\u003C/strong\u003E, is indicated for management of atrial fibrillation and should also be considered for secondary prevention of acute mesenteric ischaemia. However, given the patient is acutely symptomatic, there is no role for apixaban. CT angiography, followed by surgical and/or interventional radiological interventions are more appropriate. Additionally, initial treatment of acute mesenteric ischaemia with should be with a parenteral anticoagulant, such as IV unfractionated heparin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior mesenteric artery (SMA) angioplasty \u003C/strong\u003E(with or without stenting) may be used to treat both acute and chronic mesenteric ischaemia. However in this instance, given the patient is haemodynamically stable, visualisation of the bowel (e.g. to assess for complications) through CT angiography is the preferred first step in management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E, although least invasive, does not provide accurate or sufficient visualisation of mesenteric vessels; although it is increasingly used to diagnose abdominal aortic aneurysms, this presentation is much more concerning for bowel ischaemia and this requires urgent exclusion. Not only can intestinal gas obscure the image, but only the proximal portion of the superior mesenteric artery can be shown via ultrasound, meaning that more distal emboli cannot be detected, leading to false-negative results.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with high suspicion of intestinal ischaemia without haemodynamic instability, sepsis or peritonism, CT angiography is the preferred diagnostic test."],"references":["Schofield N, Webb ST, Varcada M, Macfie A. Acute Mesenteric Ischaemia. J Intensive Care Soc. 2014;15(3):226-230. Available at: https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/pdf/10.1177/175114371401500310","Bala M, Kashuk J, Moore EE et al. Acute mesenteric ischemia: guidelines of the World Society of Emergency Surgery. World J Emerg Surg. 2017: 12(38). Available at: https://wjes.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13017-017-0150-5#citeas","Karkkainen JM. Acute mesenteric ischemia: A challenge for the acute care surgeon. Scand J Surg 2021; 110:150\u201358. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33866891/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38949"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"200"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38949"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-21T22:33:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-21T22:35:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"200"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53480"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10